ArtfulArtichoke , 09/29/2019

Fat, Protein, and Diabetic Carb Totals by Meal

As a T1 diabetic, I used to spend several minutes before each meal doing some mental math to figure out (1) my total bolus, based on total carbs minus significant fiber plus protein and fat equivalents, then (2) my bolus strategy, based on the absorption expected from the ratios of those macros.


Most food tracker apps only provide daily macro totals or they do not provide a way to easily view/account for the fiber totals in individual meals/snacks. I tried several and found it was not worth my time to log foods since I still had to do most of the calculations myself.


In contrast, MyNetDiaryD has a fast food logging interface with a verified/unverified search option. Once you log servings, it provides a dashboard summary table that displays fat, protein, total carbs, and calculated diabetic carbs by meal, as well as a pie chart for each meal showing the same macros as ratios.


So now, I just log my servings and enter the Dcarb total plus ~25% of the protein and fat totals in my bolus wizard. Then, I decide whether to extend/split based on the meal macros pie chart, which works great as a rough absorption profile for the whole meal.


There are a lot of other awesome features, but I will just mention one more favorite - the customizable dashboard! I can add or remove components and this helps me quickly get at the information I need to make my treatment decisions. In this age of information overload and context collapse, that is absolutely invaluable!

kepardue , 09/25/2018

So close to being a perfect app for diabetics

I really like the bulk of MyNetDiary. As a HealthKit logger, this app puts EVERYTHING in, including categories that other nutrition trackers often miss, like water and caffeine.


Unfortunately a couple of items make it less than ideal to use. While it’s probably the best app for WRITING to HealthKit, it’s a terrible steward for READING data from other apps. It only reads blood glucose data and a handful of fitness items. This makes it difficult to use other apps, such as the Hidrate water tracker, with it.


Logging medications is also unnecessarily difficult. Most people take a set of medications at the same strength daily, but instead of offering a simple way to check all the medications at pre-set dosages each day, you have to go into each medication individually and enter the number of milligrams each day to record it.


Lastly, the food database has become quite a mess. It’s fairly loosely managed, so there’s little consistency with how items are listed. This leads to odd formatting such as “Product A by StoreBrand” and “StoreBrand Product B” both existing. It’s just unnecessarily inconsistent. Complicating the food listings further is that there appears to be two different descriptions, a short description and a long description. Whether or not you’ve previously selected a food seems to determine which one is shown. For instance, I may see an entry for “kellogg’s pop tarts” (where the company name is lower case, for some reason), but it’s not until you select it that you actually see that this is an entry for “pop tarts frosted s’mores toaster pastries by kellogg’s” Again, incorrect capitalization with inconsistent formatting AND there’s no way to actually know what you’re selecting before you tap on the product.

Love the recipe option

This app allows you to store recipes with a total number of servings (or grams). For example, you can save a muffin recipe that makes 12 muffins by entering all the ingredients. Developer Response ,

Hello,


Sorry about the troubles, we'll try to help. We think the overarching issue here is safety - we take it very seriously at MyNetDiary.


First of all, insulin reminders are not provided specifically for safety reasons - using built-in iPhone alarms is the most reliable way to get reminded about important things and thus this is the recommended way to get reminded about insulin.


Secondly, compared to MyFitnessPal, all foods in MyNetDiary database are verified, including their carbs count - super important for folks with diabetes and pre-diabetes. There are no food duplicates in the database. If you see some foods are not yet in the database, please send us its photos from the app (from the Custom Food screen) - we call this PhotoFoods. When you log a missing food, you just need to specify its name, calories, and carbs and we will enter all the details for you from the photos you send. We process such food updates in 24 hours or faster. We are adding and updating over 500 foods each and every day, please don't hesitate to take advantage of this service!


Thirdly, regarding "without the bun/bread" foods. MyNetDiary food database contains foods as published by vendors. If the vendor does provide nutritional information for "without the bun/bread" option, it will be in our database, verified. If the vendor does not provide nutritional information, MyNetDiary won't have it. MyFitnessPal allows "user-contributed foods", which are entered by users and not verified, so if you see some food "without the bun/bread" it may have been entered by a random person, and may or may not have correct carb count (e.g. if the person that added it subtracted wrong size bun nutrients). There are no such foods in MyNetDiary. If you eat some food without a but, we recommend creating a custom food for it.


We hope this helps! If you need more help, please don't hesitate to send email to support@mynetdiary.com or use the built-in Support screen in the app.

Highly Recommended

Our child has Type 1 and we use this to log his BGs (even though we analyze the data from his Medtronic pump and CGM) because this is much more convenient AND, most importantly to us, while he is at school we are able to get his BG numbers in real-time as our school nurse enters them via the MyNetDiary web app component and they arrive on our iPhones via this app. We’ve recommended this app to all our JDRF member friends whom have young children with T1D and they have also fallen in love with it.


PROS:

This app has been such a worthwhile investment. I like that is routinely updated. The reports are simple yet comprehensive. The screens are intrinsically useful and not cluttered. The scanner and food database are excellent resources. On the rare occasion we can’t find a food, we’ll use the MyFitnessPal food database or enter it manually. I love that I am able to enter in custom foods / recipes. The recently used foods (per meal) is very helpful.


CONS:

I was over the moon to finally see a Widget! I want the absolute quickest way possible to log a BG and get on with life.


I wish is that the widget wouldn’t take up so much vertical screen space (I have a 6+ and still feel it takes up way too much real estate). I wish it could be condensed or even configured like other apps allow their widgets to do. With this widget at the top, none of my other installed widgets are visible without scrolling.


When you hit the “+BG” button in the widget, you then have to hit the “Add BG Reading” a second time once the app opens. Again, I wish this were a bit more streamlined. It’s a great start though and I’m grateful it exists.


I also wish the BG “assign labels” (ie., before dinner, before breakfast) was more accurate. It auto-assigns the label correctly only about 20% of the time. I have no idea why.


Sometimes the carb tally for a meal doesn’t display at all (which I suspect is because I am using a serving size from a custom recipe I’ve entered - because as soon as I select something “standard / generic” in addition to my selected custom food the tally will then display).


I look forward to future updates (AND hopefully an apple watch app to log BGs)!!
